s.text: In the mid-'60s, when Dylan was at his peak, Herb Alpert was winning Album of the Year awards.
(Fogerty never won an award for the brilliant records he made with Credence Clearwater Revival three decades ago.)
In 1965, for example, Dylan went electric, abandoning folk's soft sound, earnest politics, and rabidly loyal fans.
Writing in Slate last year, Alex Ross called Time Out of Mind "the first great rock album of old age" in part because Dylan manages to sing around his weak voice.
But better to go out bleating "Not Dark Yet" than croaking through "Blowin' in the Wind" for the 10,000 th time.
As you can hear on this clip from Time Out of Mind 's "Not Dark Yet," Dylan's voice doesn't have much left.
